  "prompt": "Relation between change in celcius to change in fahrenhiet?",
  "response": "The relationship between a change in Celsius and a change in Fahrenheit is based on the conversion formula between the two temperature scales. The conversion formula is:\n\n\\[ F = \\frac{9}{5}C + 32 \\]\n\nHowever, when considering **changes** in temperature (\u0394C and \u0394F), the relationship simplifies because the \"+32\" part of the formula is an offset and does not affect the change. The relationship between the changes is:\n\n\\[ \\Delta F = \\frac{9}{5} \\Delta C \\]\n\n### Key Points:\n- A **change of 1\u00b0C** corresponds to a **change of 1.8\u00b0F**.\n- To convert a temperature change from Celsius to Fahrenheit, multiply the change in Celsius by 1.8.\n- To convert a temperature change from Fahrenheit to Celsius, divide the change in Fahrenheit by 1.8.\n\n### Example:\nIf the temperature increases by 10\u00b0C, the corresponding increase in Fahrenheit is:\n\n\\[ \\Delta F = \\frac{9}{5} \\times 10 = 18\u00b0F \\]",
